FoxHound wrote:vykromod wrote:[quote="[url=http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25446525#p25446525]It's not outright suicide, it's "suicidal" because they put excessive amounts of energy into producing huge amounts of sperm to compete with other males, to the detriment of their own long term health.That's not suicidal. Even if they could prove that the one thing causes the other, it's an unintended consequence of their own physiology.I have to agree with this. The wording suggests that it's individual reproductive behavior that is suicidal, while the details show that this isn't the case. It seems like the males will still die even if they don't mate. When I think of suicidal reproduction, I think of a spider or praying mantis being eaten by its mate.From the article:". . .there are mammals out there that engage in what researchers are terming "suicidal reproduction." The problem is that the behavior. . ."It also isn't obvious that death from immune failure is related to building up a store of sperm and then shutting off gonads, though I can see how that is plausible.In general it seems like the article would be better with a little more detail. I was surprised to see that the animals were only referred to as marsupials, with no species or common names mentioned (though I tend to skip over those anyway). Where they live wasn't mentioned either (from the paper: Australia, South America, and Papua New Guinea).Actually this first sentence from the paper helps explain things a little better:"In some marsupial genera but in no other mammals, escalating stress hormones during the breeding season cause immune system collapse and synchronized death after mating in all males (suicidal reproduction)."Personally I think this is a case where the "how" is more interesting than the "why".For example, I wonder if the escalating stress hormones are due to interacting with other individuals during the mating season. Would the males still die at the same time if they were raised alone in captivity?
